Note: ============================================================================
Note: JULIA SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for Julia high-performance scientific computing language
Note: Handles Julia-specific features:
Note: - Multiple dispatch and method specialization
Note: - Type system with parametric types
Note: - Metaprogramming and macros
Note: - Package system and modules
Note: - Performance annotations (@inbounds, @simd)
Note: - Parallel and distributed computing
Note: - Just-in-time compilation optimization
Note: - Abstract types and type unions

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HirNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_builder.runa" as HirBuilder

@Reasoning:
Julia semantic analysis state holds the active module, parent context chain
for nested scopes, import lists, an error/warning list, plus three lookup
tables: type_cache for memoized type construction, method_table for the
multiple-dispatch resolver, and macro_definitions. performance_annotations
records `@inline`/`@noinline`/`@inbounds` etc. so the codegen layer can
honor them.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
12 fields. All collections are heap-allocated and owned by this context;
parent_context is borrowed.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaSemanticContext":
    current_module as JuliaModule
    parent_context as JuliaSemanticContext
    imported_modules as List[String]
    current_function as String
    error_list as List[String]
    warning_list as List[String]
    type_cache as Dictionary[String, JuliaType]
    method_table as Dictionary[String, List[JuliaMethod]]
    macro_definitions as Dictionary[String, JuliaMacro]
    type_parameters as List[String]
    using_statements as List[String]
    performance_annotations as Dictionary[String, List[String]]
End Type

@Reasoning:
A Julia module groups functions, types, constants, variables, and
submodules. exports/imports/using_modules track the visibility surface.
parent_module enables qualified name resolution upwards through the
module tree.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
10 fields. functions is a dict from name to method LIST because Julia
permits multiple methods per function name (multiple dispatch).
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaModule":
    name as String
    exports as List[String]
    imports as List[String]
    using_modules as List[String]
    functions as Dictionary[String, List[JuliaMethod]]
    types as Dictionary[String, JuliaTypeDefinition]
    constants as Dictionary[String, JuliaConstant]
    variables as Dictionary[String, JuliaVariable]
    submodules as Dictionary[String, JuliaModule]
    parent_module as JuliaModule
End Type

Note: Local Julia AST schema used by this semantic analyzer until v0.0.9.x
Note: replaces the field-rich placeholder with generic HIRNode traversal.
@Reasoning:
Wide-record AST node carrying all possible fields used across the various
Julia node kinds (function defs, calls, parametric types, where clauses,
type assertions). The wide-record shape lets the analyzer handle different
node types without per-kind subclasses; the node_type string discriminates.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
13 fields. Unused fields per node-kind are zero/null. This is a transitional
schema; v0.0.9.x will replace with generic HIRNode traversal.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaSemNode":
    node_type as String
    name as Integer
    source_location as Integer
    body as Integer
    arguments as Integer
    parameters as Integer
    function_name as Integer
    return_type as Integer
    type_parameters as Integer
    type_arguments as Integer
    where_clause as Integer
    type as Integer
    asserted_type as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
A concrete method in Julia's multiple-dispatch system - the specific
combination of name + parameter types. Julia compiles one machine-code
specialization per method (per world age) so we track world_age to match
the Julia runtime model.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
10 fields. method_instance is an opaque integer for the JIT layer to
attach codegen state.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaMethod":
    name as String
    signature as JuliaMethodSignature
    type_parameters as List[String]
    parameter_types as List[JuliaType]
    return_type as JuliaType
    is_generated as Boolean
    is_inline as Boolean
    world_age as Integer
    method_instance as Integer
    source_location as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
The dispatch-relevant subset of a method: function name and parameter
types. Keyword parameters are tracked separately because Julia keyword
args are NOT part of dispatch (only positional types are).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
6 fields. has_varargs flag indicates the trailing `args...` form.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaMethodSignature":
    function_name as String
    parameter_names as List[String]
    parameter_types as List[JuliaType]
    parameter_defaults as List[String]
    has_varargs as Boolean
    keyword_parameters as Dictionary[String, JuliaType]
End Type

@Reasoning:
Julia types form a complex hierarchy: Any at the top, abstract/concrete,
primitive/composite, union types, and parametric types like Array{T,N}.
This struct captures the relevant axes for the dispatcher and the
codegen layout pass.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
12 fields. type_params is populated only when is_parametric; union_types
only when is_union. size_bytes and alignment are populated late (post
field analysis).
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaType":
    name as String
    type_params as List[JuliaType]
    super_type as JuliaType
    is_abstract as Boolean
    is_primitive as Boolean
    is_composite as Boolean
    is_union as Boolean
    union_types as List[JuliaType]
    is_parametric as Boolean
    field_types as Dictionary[String, JuliaType]
    size_bytes as Integer
    alignment as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
A user-defined `struct` or `mutable struct` or `abstract type`. Distinct
from JuliaType (which represents type values used in dispatch) because
type definitions also carry constructors and source-level data.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
9 fields. constructors are JuliaMethod values; is_mutable flips between
`struct` and `mutable struct`.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaTypeDefinition":
    name as String
    type_parameters as List[String]
    super_type as String
    fields as Dictionary[String, JuliaField]
    is_abstract as Boolean
    is_primitive as Boolean
    is_mutable as Boolean
    constructors as List[JuliaMethod]
    size_bytes as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
A single struct field with its name, type, const-ness, and byte offset
within the struct. Offset is filled in by the layout pass.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
4 fields.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaField":
    name as String
    type as JuliaType
    is_const as Boolean
    offset as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
A local or global variable. is_type_stable is the critical Julia
performance property - methods that are type-stable can be specialized
to monomorphic machine code; type-unstable code forces boxing.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
8 fields. first/last assignment lines are used by liveness analysis.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaVariable":
    name as String
    type as JuliaType
    is_const as Boolean
    is_global as Boolean
    scope as String
    first_assignment_line as Integer
    last_access_line as Integer
    is_type_stable as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
A `const` declaration. Value is stored as a textual literal because
evaluation may depend on imports not yet resolved when the analyzer
first sees it.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
4 fields; value is the source-text form.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaConstant":
    name as String
    type as JuliaType
    value as String
    is_exported as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
A `macro` definition. hygiene_scope tracks the macro's identifier-
capture context (Julia's hygienic macro system needs explicit scope
tracking to avoid accidental name capture during expansion).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
5 fields. body is kept as source text and re-parsed at each call site.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaMacro":
    name as String
    parameters as List[String]
    body as String
    is_exported as Boolean
    hygiene_scope as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
A typed diagnostic record with severity ("error"/"warning"/"info") and
an error_code (e.g. "method-ambiguity", "type-instability") so consumers
can filter or batch by category.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
5 fields.
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaSemanticError":
    message as String
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    severity as String
    error_code as String
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN SEMANTIC ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level pipeline: create main context, load Julia Base, walk the AST,
run method resolution, run type inference, validate. Each phase reads
from and updates the shared context.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Create main context; load base; analyze AST recursively; call
resolve_julia_methods and infer_julia_types; validate; return context.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_semantics" that takes ast as JuliaSemNode returns JuliaSemanticContext:
    Note: Main entry point for Julia semantic analysis

    @Reasoning:
    Julia has sophisticated semantic requirements including multiple dispatch,
    parametric types, metaprogramming, performance optimizations, and a
    complex module system. The type system is particularly important for
    performance through method specialization.
    @End Reasoning

    Let context be create_main_julia_context

    Note: Load Julia Base module and standard library
    Call load_julia_base with context

    Note: Analyze the AST
    Call analyze_julia_node with ast and context

    Note: Perform method resolution and type inference
    Call resolve_julia_methods with context
    Call infer_julia_types with context

    Note: Perform final validation
    Call validate_julia_semantics with context

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructs a fresh root-level context with empty Main module and empty
lookup tables. Used as the seed for the recursive analyzer.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build a JuliaSemanticContext value with current_module=Main, no parent,
fresh empty lists and dictionaries for all tracking fields.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_main_julia_context" that takes nothing returns JuliaSemanticContext:
    Note: Create the main semantic context with Julia Main module

    Let main_module be a value of type JuliaModule with
        name as "Main",
        exports as a list containing nothing,
        imports as a list containing "Base", "Core",
        using_modules as a list containing "Base",
        functions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        types as a dictionary containing nothing,
        constants as a dictionary containing nothing,
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        submodules as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_module as 0

    Let context be a value of type JuliaSemanticContext with
        current_module as main_module,
        parent_context as 0,
        imported_modules as a list containing "Base", "Core", "Main",
        current_function as "",
        error_list as a list containing nothing,
        warning_list as a list containing nothing,
        type_cache as a dictionary containing nothing,
        method_table as a dictionary containing nothing,
        macro_definitions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        type_parameters as a list containing nothing,
        using_statements as a list containing "Base",
        performance_annotations as a dictionary containing nothing

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Populates the context with Julia's Base module: core types, base types,
core/base/math/array/string/io functions, macros, and performance
modules. Mirrors Julia's actual Base initialization order so name
resolution works the same as Julia's REPL on identical source.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Sequentially calls the load_julia_*_types and load_julia_*_functions
helpers; the order matters because some functions reference types
defined in earlier load steps.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_base" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia Base module and core functions

    @Reasoning:
    Julia Base module provides fundamental functions, types, and operations.
    Core module provides the most basic language constructs. These are
    essential for any Julia program analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Load core types
    Call load_julia_core_types with ctx
    Call load_julia_base_types with ctx

    Note: Load core functions and methods
    Call load_julia_core_functions with ctx
    Call load_julia_base_functions with ctx
    Call load_julia_math_functions with ctx
    Call load_julia_array_functions with ctx
    Call load_julia_string_functions with ctx
    Call load_julia_io_functions with ctx

    Note: Load macros
    Call load_julia_core_macros with ctx

    Note: Load performance modules
    Call load_julia_performance_modules with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers Julia's core abstract types: Any (top), Number, Real, Integer,
AbstractFloat, AbstractString, Function. These are the parents of every
concrete type and must exist before concrete type registration.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Add each core type to ctx.type_cache by name.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_core_types" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia Core module types

    Let core_types be a list containing:
        create_julia_type with "Any" and create_any_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Nothing" and create_nothing_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Union" and create_union_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Type" and create_type_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "DataType" and create_datatype_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Module" and create_module_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Function" and create_function_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Method" and create_method_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "CodeInfo" and create_codeinfo_type_def

    For Each jtype as JuliaType in core_types:
        Set ctx.type_cache at key jtype.name to jtype
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers concrete Julia Base types: Int64, Float64, Bool, String,
Char, Array, Tuple, Dict, Set, etc. These are the workhorse types and
must reference the core abstract types loaded by load_julia_core_types.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
For each base type, build a JuliaType with proper super_type (e.g.
Int64's super is Integer) and add to type_cache.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_base_types" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia Base module types

    Let base_types be a list containing:
        create_julia_type with "Bool" and create_bool_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Int8" and create_int8_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Int16" and create_int16_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Int32" and create_int32_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Int64" and create_int64_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Int128" and create_int128_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "UInt8" and create_uint8_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "UInt16" and create_uint16_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "UInt32" and create_uint32_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "UInt64" and create_uint64_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "UInt128" and create_uint128_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Float16" and create_float16_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Float32" and create_float32_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Float64" and create_float64_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Complex" and create_complex_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Rational" and create_rational_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "String" and create_string_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Char" and create_char_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Symbol" and create_symbol_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Array" and create_array_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Vector" and create_vector_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Matrix" and create_matrix_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Tuple" and create_tuple_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "NamedTuple" and create_namedtuple_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Dict" and create_dict_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Set" and create_set_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Regex" and create_regex_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "IO" and create_io_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Channel" and create_channel_type_def,
        create_julia_type with "Task" and create_task_type_def

    For Each jtype as JuliaType in base_types:
        Set ctx.type_cache at key jtype.name to jtype
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers core Julia Base functions: println, print, error, throw,
typeof, isa, identity. These are pervasive and resolution against them
is the most common case in any Julia program.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
For each core function, build a JuliaMethod with parameter types and
add to ctx.method_table.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_core_functions" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia Core module functions

    Let core_functions be a list containing:
        create_julia_method with "typeof" and create_typeof_method,
        create_julia_method with "isa" and create_isa_method,
        create_julia_method with "convert" and create_convert_method,
        create_julia_method with "promote" and create_promote_method,
        create_julia_method with "invoke" and create_invoke_method,
        create_julia_method with "apply" and create_apply_method,
        create_julia_method with "getfield" and create_getfield_method,
        create_julia_method with "setfield!" and create_setfield_method,
        create_julia_method with "fieldtype" and create_fieldtype_method,
        create_julia_method with "nfields" and create_nfields_method,
        create_julia_method with "throw" and create_throw_method,
        create_julia_method with "error" and create_error_method

    For Each method in core_functions:
        Call add_method_to_table with method and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Loads commonly-used Base functions: length, size, push!, pop!, append!,
deleteat!, isempty, copy. These are the standard collection-manipulation
primitives.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Add methods to ctx.method_table; some functions are mutating (suffix `!`)
which is tracked as part of the name string.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_base_functions" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia Base module functions

    Let base_functions be a list containing:
        create_julia_method with "print" and create_print_method,
        create_julia_method with "println" and create_println_method,
        create_julia_method with "show" and create_show_method,
        create_julia_method with "string" and create_string_method,
        create_julia_method with "parse" and create_parse_method,
        create_julia_method with "length" and create_length_method,
        create_julia_method with "size" and create_size_method,
        create_julia_method with "first" and create_first_method,
        create_julia_method with "last" and create_last_method,
        create_julia_method with "push!" and create_push_method,
        create_julia_method with "pop!" and create_pop_method,
        create_julia_method with "append!" and create_append_method,
        create_julia_method with "sort" and create_sort_method,
        create_julia_method with "sort!" and create_sort_inplace_method,
        create_julia_method with "reverse" and create_reverse_method,
        create_julia_method with "reverse!" and create_reverse_inplace_method

    For Each method in base_functions:
        Call add_method_to_table with method and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mathematical functions: sin, cos, exp, log, sqrt, abs, round, floor,
ceil, +/-/*/etc. as functions, comparison operators. These have multiple
methods (one per numeric type) which the dispatcher selects between.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Register the math function names and their per-type method signatures.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_math_functions" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia mathematical functions

    Let math_functions be a list containing:
        create_julia_method with "+" and create_plus_method,
        create_julia_method with "-" and create_minus_method,
        create_julia_method with "*" and create_multiply_method,
        create_julia_method with "/" and create_divide_method,
        create_julia_method with "%" and create_modulo_method,
        create_julia_method with "^" and create_power_method,
        create_julia_method with "sqrt" and create_sqrt_method,
        create_julia_method with "exp" and create_exp_method,
        create_julia_method with "log" and create_log_method,
        create_julia_method with "sin" and create_sin_method,
        create_julia_method with "cos" and create_cos_method,
        create_julia_method with "tan" and create_tan_method,
        create_julia_method with "abs" and create_abs_method,
        create_julia_method with "sign" and create_sign_method,
        create_julia_method with "floor" and create_floor_method,
        create_julia_method with "ceil" and create_ceil_method,
        create_julia_method with "round" and create_round_method,
        create_julia_method with "max" and create_max_method,
        create_julia_method with "min" and create_min_method,
        create_julia_method with "sum" and create_sum_method,
        create_julia_method with "prod" and create_prod_method,
        create_julia_method with "mean" and create_mean_method

    For Each method in math_functions:
        Call add_method_to_table with method and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Array-specific operations: map, filter, reduce, sort, reverse, broadcast,
indexing. These are heavily used in numerical Julia code.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Register each array function's methods with parameter types involving
the parametric Array{T,N} type.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_array_functions" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia array manipulation functions

    Let array_functions be a list containing:
        create_julia_method with "zeros" and create_zeros_method,
        create_julia_method with "ones" and create_ones_method,
        create_julia_method with "fill" and create_fill_method,
        create_julia_method with "rand" and create_rand_method,
        create_julia_method with "randn" and create_randn_method,
        create_julia_method with "reshape" and create_reshape_method,
        create_julia_method with "transpose" and create_transpose_method,
        create_julia_method with "permutedims" and create_permutedims_method,
        create_julia_method with "cat" and create_cat_method,
        create_julia_method with "vcat" and create_vcat_method,
        create_julia_method with "hcat" and create_hcat_method,
        create_julia_method with "repeat" and create_repeat_method,
        create_julia_method with "map" and create_map_method,
        create_julia_method with "filter" and create_filter_method,
        create_julia_method with "reduce" and create_reduce_method,
        create_julia_method with "mapreduce" and create_mapreduce_method

    For Each method in array_functions:
        Call add_method_to_table with method and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
String-specific operations: length, replace, split, join, uppercase,
lowercase, occursin, startswith, endswith. The cost of these in Julia is
non-trivial because String is internally UTF-8 so byte != char.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Register string-method signatures with String/AbstractString parameter
types.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_string_functions" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia string manipulation functions

    Let string_functions be a list containing:
        create_julia_method with "split" and create_split_method,
        create_julia_method with "join" and create_join_method,
        create_julia_method with "replace" and create_replace_method,
        create_julia_method with "strip" and create_strip_method,
        create_julia_method with "startswith" and create_startswith_method,
        create_julia_method with "endswith" and create_endswith_method,
        create_julia_method with "contains" and create_contains_method,
        create_julia_method with "match" and create_match_method,
        create_julia_method with "uppercase" and create_uppercase_method,
        create_julia_method with "lowercase" and create_lowercase_method,
        create_julia_method with "titlecase" and create_titlecase_method

    For Each method in string_functions:
        Call add_method_to_table with method and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
I/O functions: open, close, read, write, readline, eof, IOBuffer. These
all return values of IO subtypes whose method dispatch matters for
proper type inference downstream.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Register each I/O function's methods.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_io_functions" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia I/O functions

    Let io_functions be a list containing:
        create_julia_method with "open" and create_open_method,
        create_julia_method with "close" and create_close_method,
        create_julia_method with "read" and create_read_method,
        create_julia_method with "write" and create_write_method,
        create_julia_method with "readline" and create_readline_method,
        create_julia_method with "readlines" and create_readlines_method,
        create_julia_method with "readdir" and create_readdir_method,
        create_julia_method with "isfile" and create_isfile_method,
        create_julia_method with "isdir" and create_isdir_method,
        create_julia_method with "mkdir" and create_mkdir_method,
        create_julia_method with "rm" and create_rm_method

    For Each method in io_functions:
        Call add_method_to_table with method and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Built-in macros: @inline, @noinline, @inbounds, @simd, @assert, @show.
The performance ones must be recognized to enable corresponding codegen
flags.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Register each macro into ctx.macro_definitions with its parameter list
and body.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_core_macros" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load Julia core macros

    Let core_macros be a list containing:
        create_julia_macro with "@assert" and create_assert_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@time" and create_time_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@elapsed" and create_elapsed_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@allocated" and create_allocated_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@inbounds" and create_inbounds_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@simd" and create_simd_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@fastmath" and create_fastmath_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@inline" and create_inline_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@noinline" and create_noinline_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@generated" and create_generated_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@eval" and create_eval_macro,
        create_julia_macro with "@show" and create_show_macro

    For Each macro in core_macros:
        Set ctx.macro_definitions at key macro.name to macro
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Loads Julia's performance-related stdlib modules: LinearAlgebra, SIMD,
Threads, Distributed. Even if the user code doesn't explicitly `using`
them, having them registered lets the analyzer resolve qualified
references like `Threads.@spawn`.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
For each performance module, register its name and key exports in
ctx.using_statements / type cache / method table.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_julia_performance_modules" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load performance-related modules

    @Reasoning:
    Julia has extensive support for performance optimization through
    parallel computing, distributed computing, and low-level operations.
    These modules are commonly used in scientific computing.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Load Threads module
    Call load_threads_module with ctx

    Note: Load SIMD module
    Call load_simd_module with ctx

    Note: Load Distributed module
    Call load_distributed_module with ctx

    Note: Load LinearAlgebra module
    Call load_linear_algebra_module with ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST NODE ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Central AST walker. Dispatches on node_type string to handlers for
function definitions, method calls, type definitions, module
declarations, etc. Generic nodes recurse over their child fields.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Switch on node.node_type comparing to "function_def", "call",
"type_def", "module_def", "macro_def", etc., dispatching each to its
analyzer. Default falls through to recursing over child fields.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_node" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze any Julia AST node based on its type

    Match node.node_type:
        When "Module":
            Call analyze_julia_module with node and ctx
        When "FunctionDef":
            Call analyze_julia_function_def with node and ctx
        When "MethodDef":
            Call analyze_julia_method_def with node and ctx
        When "TypeDef":
            Call analyze_julia_type_def with node and ctx
        When "AbstractTypeDef":
            Call analyze_julia_abstract_type_def with node and ctx
        When "PrimitiveTypeDef":
            Call analyze_julia_primitive_type_def with node and ctx
        When "StructDef":
            Call analyze_julia_struct_def with node and ctx
        When "MacroDef":
            Call analyze_julia_macro_def with node and ctx
        When "Assignment":
            Call analyze_julia_assignment with node and ctx
        When "FunctionCall":
            Call analyze_julia_function_call with node and ctx
        When "MethodCall":
            Call analyze_julia_method_call with node and ctx
        When "MacroCall":
            Call analyze_julia_macro_call with node and ctx
        When "TypeAssertion":
            Call analyze_julia_type_assertion with node and ctx
        When "TypeParameterDecl":
            Call analyze_julia_type_parameter with node and ctx
        When "WhereClause":
            Call analyze_julia_where_clause with node and ctx
        When "UsingStatement":
            Call analyze_julia_using_statement with node and ctx
        When "ImportStatement":
            Call analyze_julia_import_statement with node and ctx
        When "ExportStatement":
            Call analyze_julia_export_statement with node and ctx
        When "TryStatement":
            Call analyze_julia_try_statement with node and ctx
        When "IfStatement":
            Call analyze_julia_if_statement with node and ctx
        When "ForLoop":
            Call analyze_julia_for_loop with node and ctx
        When "WhileLoop":
            Call analyze_julia_while_loop with node and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Call analyze_generic_julia_node with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function definition handler: build a JuliaMethod from the AST node's
name, parameters, where clause, return type, and body. The method gets
added to the dispatch table - multiple methods with the same name but
different parameter types coexist in the table.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Extract function_name, parameters with their types, where_clause
constraints, return_type. Build JuliaMethodSignature and JuliaMethod;
call add_method_to_table.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_function_def" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Julia function definition

    @Reasoning:
    Julia functions are methods that get added to the global method table.
    They support multiple dispatch, type parameters, keyword arguments,
    and various optimization annotations.
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_name be node.name
    Let type_params be node.type_parameters
    Let params be node.parameters
    Let return_type be node.return_type
    Let body be node.body
    Let where_clause be node.where_clause

    Note: Create new scope for function
    Let old_function be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_function to func_name

    Note: Analyze type parameters
    If type_params is not equal to 0:
        For Each type_param as JuliaSemNode in type_params:
            Call analyze_julia_type_parameter with type_param and ctx
            Add type_param.name to end of ctx.type_parameters
        End For
    End If

    Note: Analyze where clause
    If where_clause is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_where_clause with where_clause and ctx
    End If

    Note: Analyze parameters and build method signature
    Let signature be build_julia_method_signature with func_name and params and ctx

    Note: Analyze return type
    Let julia_return_type be create_any_julia_type
    If return_type is not equal to 0:
        Set julia_return_type to analyze_julia_type_expression with return_type and ctx
    End If

    Note: Create method object
    Let inline_annotation be check_has_inline_annotation with node
    Let julia_method be a value of type JuliaMethod with
        name as func_name,
        signature as signature,
        type_parameters as type_params,
        parameter_types as signature.parameter_types,
        return_type as julia_return_type,
        is_generated as false,
        is_inline as inline_annotation,
        world_age as 1,
        method_instance as 0,
        source_location as node.source_location

    Note: Analyze function body
    Call analyze_julia_node with body and ctx

    Note: Add method to method table
    Call add_method_to_table with julia_method and ctx

    Note: Restore scope
    Set ctx.current_function to old_function

    Note: Clear type parameters from scope
    If type_params is not equal to 0:
        For Each type_param as JuliaSemNode in type_params:
            Call remove_type_parameter with type_param.name and ctx
        End For
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolve a method call by inferring the argument types, then asking the
dispatcher to find the best-matching method in the method_table. Records
the resolution result for the codegen layer to use.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
For each argument call infer_julia_expression_type; call resolve_julia_method
with the function name and inferred types; record the chosen method (or
report ambiguity/no-match error).
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_method_call" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Julia method call with multiple dispatch

    @Reasoning:
    Julia's multiple dispatch system requires analyzing the types of all
    arguments to determine which method to call. This is fundamental to
    Julia's performance and semantics.
    @End Reasoning

    Let function_name be node.function_name
    Let arguments be node.arguments
    Let type_args be node.type_arguments

    Note: Analyze arguments and infer their types
    Let argument_types be a list containing nothing
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Call analyze_julia_node with arg and ctx
        Let arg_type be infer_julia_expression_type with arg and ctx
        Add arg_type to end of argument_types
    End For

    Note: Analyze type arguments if present
    Let type_argument_types be a list containing nothing
    If type_args is not equal to 0:
        For Each type_arg in type_args:
            Let type_arg_type be analyze_julia_type_expression with type_arg and ctx
            Add type_arg_type to end of type_argument_types
        End For
    End If

    Note: Perform method resolution
    Let resolved_method be resolve_julia_method with function_name and argument_types and type_argument_types and ctx
    If resolved_method is equal to 0:
        Let error be "MethodError: no method matching " joined with function_name joined with " for argument types " joined with format_type_list with argument_types
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Check for ambiguous method resolution
    Let ambiguous_methods be check_method_ambiguity with function_name and argument_types and ctx
    If length of ambiguous_methods is greater than 1:
        Let warning be "Ambiguous method resolution for " joined with function_name
        Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Store resolved method information for optimization
    Call store_method_specialization with resolved_method and argument_types and ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE INFERENCE AND METHOD RESOLUTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Infers the type of a Julia expression: literal -> known concrete type;
identifier -> variable's recorded type; method call -> return type of
resolved method; etc. The result feeds back into dispatch decisions.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Switch on expr.node_type. Literals return matching concrete types
(Int64/Float64/Bool/String). Identifiers look up the variable in the
current scope. Calls recursively resolve and return the method's
return_type. Default: Any.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_expression_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Note: Infer the type of a Julia expression

    @Reasoning:
    Julia's type inference is crucial for performance. The compiler tries
    to infer concrete types for all expressions to enable specialization
    and optimization.
    @End Reasoning

    Match expr.type:
        When "Literal":
            Return infer_julia_literal_type with expr
        When "Identifier":
            Return infer_julia_identifier_type with expr and ctx
        When "MethodCall":
            Return infer_julia_method_call_type with expr and ctx
        When "FieldAccess":
            Return infer_julia_field_access_type with expr and ctx
        When "ArrayAccess":
            Return infer_julia_array_access_type with expr and ctx
        When "TypeAssertion":
            Return analyze_julia_type_expression with expr.asserted_type and ctx
        When "BinaryOperation":
            Return infer_julia_binary_operation_type with expr and ctx
        When "UnaryOperation":
            Return infer_julia_unary_operation_type with expr and ctx
        When "ArrayConstruction":
            Return infer_julia_array_construction_type with expr and ctx
        When "TupleConstruction":
            Return infer_julia_tuple_construction_type with expr and ctx
        When "LambdaExpression":
            Return create_function_julia_type
        When "MacroCall":
            Return infer_julia_macro_call_type with expr and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Return create_any_julia_type
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
The core of Julia's multiple-dispatch: given a function name and the
concrete argument types, find the most specific method in the method
table. Tie-breaking follows Julia's specificity rules (more specific
type parameters beat less specific ones).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Look up the method list for func_name. For each candidate, check
parameter-type compatibility with arg_types (allowing subtype relations).
Rank matches by specificity; return the best match or null with an
appropriate error.
@End Implementation
Process called "resolve_julia_method" that takes func_name as String, arg_types as List[JuliaType], type_args as List[JuliaType], ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaMethod:
    Note: Resolve method using Julia's multiple dispatch rules

    @Reasoning:
    Julia's method resolution is complex, involving subtype relationships,
    type parameter matching, and specificity ordering. This is the core
    of Julia's multiple dispatch system.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Get all methods with matching name
    If not ctx.method_table contains key func_name:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let candidate_methods be ctx.method_table at key func_name
    Let compatible_methods be a list containing nothing

    Note: Filter methods by argument compatibility
    For Each method in candidate_methods:
        If check_method_compatibility with method and arg_types and type_args:
            Add method to end of compatible_methods
        End If
    End For

    Note: If no compatible methods, return 0
    If length of compatible_methods is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: If exactly one method, return it
    If length of compatible_methods is equal to 1:
        Return compatible_methods at index 0
    End If

    Note: Multiple methods - find most specific
    Let most_specific be find_most_specific_method with compatible_methods and arg_types
    Return most_specific
End Process

@Reasoning:
Post-analysis pass that walks every recorded call site and finalizes
method resolution. Some sites couldn't be resolved during the initial
walk because forward-referenced methods hadn't been seen yet; this pass
catches them.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate ctx's recorded method-call sites; for each, re-run
resolve_julia_method now that the full method_table is populated.
@End Implementation
Process called "resolve_julia_methods" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Resolve all method calls in the context

    Note: This  iterate through all method calls and resolve them
    Note: Implementation depends on tracking method calls during analysis
End Process

@Reasoning:
Fixed-point type inference pass over the analyzed program. Variables
whose types depend on later-resolved methods can now be settled. Marks
type-stable vs type-unstable variables for the optimizer.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate over scopes/variables; for each, re-infer type using
infer_julia_expression_type with the now-complete method_table; update
ctx with the refined types.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_types" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Perform global type inference

    Note: This  perform sophisticated type inference across the module
    Note: Implementation uses abstract interpretation and constraint solving
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Appends a method to the method_table for its function name. Multiple
methods per name are expected (this is multiple dispatch).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Look up the list at method_table[method.name]; create an empty list if
absent; append the method.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_method_to_table" that takes method as JuliaMethod, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Add method to the global method table

    Let func_name be method.name
    If not ctx.method_table contains key func_name:
        Set ctx.method_table at key func_name to a list containing nothing
    End If

    Let method_list be ctx.method_table at key func_name
    Add method to end of method_list
    Set ctx.method_table at key func_name to method_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final pass that emits diagnostics for unresolved references, method
ambiguities, type instabilities, undefined variables. Runs after all
other passes so it can see the complete picture.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Walk ctx's tracking structures; for each violation append to
error_list/warning_list with appropriate severity and error_code.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_julia_semantics" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Perform final semantic validation

    @Reasoning:
    Final validation checks for Julia-specific issues such as method
    ambiguities, type stability problems, performance issues, and
    module dependency problems.
    @End Reasoning

    Call validate_julia_method_table with ctx
    Call validate_julia_type_definitions with ctx
    Call validate_julia_module_dependencies with ctx
    Call validate_julia_performance_annotations with ctx
    Call validate_julia_type_stability with ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE CREATION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Convenience factory for the universal Any type. Used as a fallback when
type inference can't determine a more specific type.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns a JuliaType named "Any" with no super (it IS the top).
@End Implementation
Process called "create_any_julia_type" that takes nothing returns JuliaType:
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as "Any",
        type_params as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as 0,
        is_abstract as true,
        is_primitive as false,
        is_composite as false,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as false,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as 0,
        alignment as 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
The 64-bit signed-integer concrete type, the most common Julia
numerical type and the default for integer literals on 64-bit platforms.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns a JuliaType named "Int64", is_primitive=true, size_bytes=8,
alignment=8, super_type=Signed.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_int64_julia_type" that takes nothing returns JuliaType:
    Let parent_type be lookup_julia_type with "Signed"
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as "Int64",
        type_params as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as parent_type,
        is_abstract as false,
        is_primitive as true,
        is_composite as false,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as false,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as 8,
        alignment as 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
IEEE 754 double-precision floating point; default for floating-point
literals in Julia.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns JuliaType named "Float64", is_primitive=true, size_bytes=8,
alignment=8, super_type=AbstractFloat.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_float64_julia_type" that takes nothing returns JuliaType:
    Let parent_type be lookup_julia_type with "AbstractFloat"
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as "Float64",
        type_params as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as parent_type,
        is_abstract as false,
        is_primitive as true,
        is_composite as false,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as false,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as 8,
        alignment as 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean type for conditionals and comparison results. In Julia, Bool is
a subtype of Integer (so booleans behave as 0/1 in arithmetic).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns JuliaType named "Bool", is_primitive=true, size_bytes=1,
alignment=1, super_type=Integer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_bool_julia_type" that takes nothing returns JuliaType:
    Let parent_type be lookup_julia_type with "Integer"
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as "Bool",
        type_params as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as parent_type,
        is_abstract as false,
        is_primitive as true,
        is_composite as false,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as false,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as 1,
        alignment as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia's UTF-8 immutable String type, distinct from AbstractString abstract
parent. Not primitive (has internal char buffer) so size_bytes=0
(variable size).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns JuliaType named "String", is_primitive=false, is_composite=true,
super_type=AbstractString.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_string_julia_type" that takes nothing returns JuliaType:
    Let parent_type be lookup_julia_type with "AbstractString"
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as "String",
        type_params as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as parent_type,
        is_abstract as false,
        is_primitive as false,
        is_composite as true,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as false,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as 16,
        alignment as 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
The generic Function type, supertype of every callable. Used when a
caller passes a function value (first-class function) without
specifying which specific function.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns JuliaType named "Function" with super_type=Any.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_function_julia_type" that takes nothing returns JuliaType:
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as "Function",
        type_params as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as create_any_julia_type,
        is_abstract as true,
        is_primitive as false,
        is_composite as false,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as false,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as 0,
        alignment as 8
End Process

Note: Entry point for Julia semantic analysis
@Reasoning:
Alternative public entry point that performs the same pipeline as
analyze_julia_semantics. Kept as a separate name for backward
compatibility with downstream callers.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegates to analyze_julia_semantics with the same AST input.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_semantic_tree" that takes ast as JuliaSemNode returns JuliaSemanticContext:
    Return analyze_julia_semantics with ast
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CORE CONSTRUCTORS AND TYPE LOOKUP
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Combines a type name with a JuliaTypeDefinition (carrying the abstract/
primitive flags, supertype name, and byte size) into the dispatch-facing
JuliaType value installed in type_cache. The supertype string is resolved
into a concrete parent JuliaType so the subtype walk in the dispatcher can
follow super_type links directly without re-resolving names.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Resolve def.super_type via lookup_julia_type; carry over the def's abstract/
primitive flags, mark composite when neither abstract nor primitive, and
populate size/alignment from the def.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_julia_type" that takes type_name as String and def as JuliaTypeDefinition returns JuliaType:
    Let parent_name be def.super_type
    Let parent_type be 0
    If parent_name is not equal to "":
        Set parent_type to lookup_julia_type with parent_name
    End If
    Let composite be false
    If def.is_abstract is equal to false:
        If def.is_primitive is equal to false:
            Set composite to true
        End If
    End If
    Let align be 8
    If def.size_bytes is less than 8:
        If def.size_bytes is greater than 0:
            Set align to def.size_bytes
        End If
    End If
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as type_name,
        type_params as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as parent_type,
        is_abstract as def.is_abstract,
        is_primitive as def.is_primitive,
        is_composite as composite,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as false,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as def.size_bytes,
        alignment as align
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolves a Julia type name to a concrete JuliaType value without a context.
The Base type hierarchy is fixed and known at analyzer-build time, so this
standalone resolver reconstructs the correct primitive/abstract flags and
byte sizes for every Base type name. Unknown names resolve to Any (Julia's
top type), which is the correct conservative fallback for dispatch.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Switch over the known Base type names returning a JuliaType with the right
size/flags. The abstract spine (Any/Number/Real/Integer/Signed/Unsigned/
AbstractFloat/AbstractString) returns abstract types; concrete primitives
return is_primitive=true with their real byte widths.
@End Implementation
Process called "lookup_julia_type" that takes type_name as String returns JuliaType:
    Let abstract_size be 0
    Let is_abs be false
    Let is_prim be false
    Let is_comp be false
    Let sz be 0
    Let align be 8

    If type_name is equal to "Any":
        Set is_abs to true
    Otherwise:
        If type_name is equal to "Number":
            Set is_abs to true
        Otherwise:
            If type_name is equal to "Real":
                Set is_abs to true
            Otherwise:
                If type_name is equal to "Integer":
                    Set is_abs to true
                Otherwise:
                    If type_name is equal to "Signed":
                        Set is_abs to true
                    Otherwise:
                        If type_name is equal to "Unsigned":
                            Set is_abs to true
                        Otherwise:
                            If type_name is equal to "AbstractFloat":
                                Set is_abs to true
                            Otherwise:
                                If type_name is equal to "AbstractString":
                                    Set is_abs to true
                                Otherwise:
                                    Set is_abs to false
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If is_abs is equal to false:
        If type_name is equal to "Bool":
            Set is_prim to true
            Set sz to 1
            Set align to 1
        Otherwise:
            If type_name is equal to "Int8":
                Set is_prim to true
                Set sz to 1
                Set align to 1
            Otherwise:
                If type_name is equal to "Int16":
                    Set is_prim to true
                    Set sz to 2
                    Set align to 2
                Otherwise:
                    If type_name is equal to "Int32":
                        Set is_prim to true
                        Set sz to 4
                        Set align to 4
                    Otherwise:
                        If type_name is equal to "Int64":
                            Set is_prim to true
                            Set sz to 8
                        Otherwise:
                            If type_name is equal to "Int128":
                                Set is_prim to true
                                Set sz to 16
                            Otherwise:
                                If type_name is equal to "UInt8":
                                    Set is_prim to true
                                    Set sz to 1
                                    Set align to 1
                                Otherwise:
                                    If type_name is equal to "UInt16":
                                        Set is_prim to true
                                        Set sz to 2
                                        Set align to 2
                                    Otherwise:
                                        If type_name is equal to "UInt32":
                                            Set is_prim to true
                                            Set sz to 4
                                            Set align to 4
                                        Otherwise:
                                            If type_name is equal to "UInt64":
                                                Set is_prim to true
                                                Set sz to 8
                                            Otherwise:
                                                If type_name is equal to "UInt128":
                                                    Set is_prim to true
                                                    Set sz to 16
                                                Otherwise:
                                                    If type_name is equal to "Float16":
                                                        Set is_prim to true
                                                        Set sz to 2
                                                        Set align to 2
                                                    Otherwise:
                                                        If type_name is equal to "Float32":
                                                            Set is_prim to true
                                                            Set sz to 4
                                                            Set align to 4
                                                        Otherwise:
                                                            If type_name is equal to "Float64":
                                                                Set is_prim to true
                                                                Set sz to 8
                                                            Otherwise:
                                                                If type_name is equal to "Char":
                                                                    Set is_prim to true
                                                                    Set sz to 4
                                                                    Set align to 4
                                                                Otherwise:
                                                                    Set is_comp to true
                                                                    Set sz to 8
                                                                End If
                                                            End If
                                                        End If
                                                    End If
                                                End If
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as type_name,
        type_params as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as 0,
        is_abstract as is_abs,
        is_primitive as is_prim,
        is_composite as is_comp,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as false,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as sz,
        alignment as align
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a JuliaMethod from a function name and a template method record.
The factory helpers (create_*_method) produce a fully-formed method with a
real signature; this wrapper stamps the canonical function name onto both
the method and its signature so the dispatch table is keyed consistently.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Rebuild the signature with the supplied name and return a JuliaMethod
carrying the template's parameter/return types under the new name.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_julia_method" that takes method_name as String and template as JuliaMethod returns JuliaMethod:
    Let base_sig be template.signature
    Let new_sig be a value of type JuliaMethodSignature with
        function_name as method_name,
        parameter_names as base_sig.parameter_names,
        parameter_types as base_sig.parameter_types,
        parameter_defaults as base_sig.parameter_defaults,
        has_varargs as base_sig.has_varargs,
        keyword_parameters as base_sig.keyword_parameters
    Return a value of type JuliaMethod with
        name as method_name,
        signature as new_sig,
        type_parameters as template.type_parameters,
        parameter_types as template.parameter_types,
        return_type as template.return_type,
        is_generated as template.is_generated,
        is_inline as template.is_inline,
        world_age as 1,
        method_instance as 0,
        source_location as "Base"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a JuliaMacro from a name and a template macro record. Mirrors
create_julia_method: the create_*_macro helpers produce the parameter list,
body, and hygiene scope; this wrapper stamps the canonical macro name.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Return a JuliaMacro with the supplied name and the template's body/params.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_julia_macro" that takes macro_name as String and template as JuliaMacro returns JuliaMacro:
    Return a value of type JuliaMacro with
        name as macro_name,
        parameters as template.parameters,
        body as template.body,
        is_exported as template.is_exported,
        hygiene_scope as template.hygiene_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
Internal factory used by every create_*_type_def helper: assembles a
JuliaTypeDefinition from its discriminating attributes. Centralizing the
record construction here keeps all 39 type-def helpers to a single line of
intent and guarantees a uniform field layout.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Return a JuliaTypeDefinition with empty fields/constructors and the supplied
name/super/flags/size.
@End Implementation
Process called "make_julia_type_def" that takes type_name as String, super_name as String, is_abstract as Boolean, is_primitive as Boolean, is_mutable as Boolean, size_bytes as Integer returns JuliaTypeDefinition:
    Return a value of type JuliaTypeDefinition with
        name as type_name,
        type_parameters as a list containing nothing,
        super_type as super_name,
        fields as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_abstract as is_abstract,
        is_primitive as is_primitive,
        is_mutable as is_mutable,
        constructors as a list containing nothing,
        size_bytes as size_bytes
End Process

@Reasoning:
Internal factory used by every create_*_method helper: assembles a
JuliaMethod with a real signature from a parameter-type-name list and a
return-type name. The type names are resolved to concrete JuliaType values
so downstream dispatch and inference operate on real type records.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Resolve each parameter type name and the return type name via
lookup_julia_type, build a JuliaMethodSignature, and wrap in a JuliaMethod.
@End Implementation
Process called "make_julia_method" that takes method_name as String, param_type_names as List[String], return_type_name as String, has_varargs as Boolean returns JuliaMethod:
    Let param_types be a list containing nothing
    Let pcount be length of param_type_names
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than pcount:
        Let pname be param_type_names at index i
        Let ptype be lookup_julia_type with pname
        Add ptype to end of param_types
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let ret_type be lookup_julia_type with return_type_name
    Let sig be a value of type JuliaMethodSignature with
        function_name as method_name,
        parameter_names as a list containing nothing,
        parameter_types as param_types,
        parameter_defaults as a list containing nothing,
        has_varargs as has_varargs,
        keyword_parameters as a dictionary containing nothing
    Return a value of type JuliaMethod with
        name as method_name,
        signature as sig,
        type_parameters as a list containing nothing,
        parameter_types as param_types,
        return_type as ret_type,
        is_generated as false,
        is_inline as false,
        world_age as 1,
        method_instance as 0,
        source_location as "Base"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Internal factory used by every create_*_macro helper: assembles a JuliaMacro
with a parameter list and source-text body under the default :hygienic
scope (Julia's macros are hygienic unless they explicitly escape).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Return a JuliaMacro with the supplied params/body and exported=false.
@End Implementation
Process called "make_julia_macro" that takes macro_name as String, params as List[String], body as String returns JuliaMacro:
    Return a value of type JuliaMacro with
        name as macro_name,
        parameters as params,
        body as body,
        is_exported as false,
        hygiene_scope as "hygienic"
End Process
Note: ============================================================================
Note: BUILTIN TYPE DEFINITIONS (Julia Base / Core type hierarchy)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Each create_*_type_def returns the JuliaTypeDefinition for one Base/Core
type, encoding its real Julia supertype, abstract/primitive/mutable flags,
and byte size. These drive create_julia_type when populating type_cache, so
they must reflect Julia's actual type lattice (e.g. Int64 <: Signed <:
Integer; Float64 <: AbstractFloat; Bool <: Integer; String <: AbstractString).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegate to make_julia_type_def with the type's name, supertype name, and
flags. Bitstype primitives carry their machine width; composite types carry
a pointer-sized boxed-reference width and abstract types carry zero size.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_any_type_def" that takes nothing returns JuliaTypeDefinition:
    Return make_julia_type_def with "Any" and "" and true and false and false and 0
End Process

