Note: ============================================================================
Note: BUILTIN MACRO DEFINITIONS (Julia Base macros)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Each create_*_macro returns the JuliaMacro template for one Base macro. The
performance macros (@inbounds/@simd/@fastmath/@inline/@noinline) wrap a
single code expression and carry a body marker the codegen layer reads to
set the corresponding optimization flag. Measurement macros (@time/@elapsed/
@allocated) wrap an expression and synthesize timing/allocation accounting.
@assert wraps a condition (plus optional message); @eval/@show/@generated
carry their expression argument.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegate to make_julia_macro with the macro name, its parameter-name list,
and the source-text expansion body.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_assert_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@assert" and (a list containing "cond", "msg") and "cond || throw(AssertionError(msg))"
End Process

Process called "create_time_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@time" and (a list containing "expr") and "local t0 = time_ns(); local v = expr; local t1 = time_ns(); println(t1 - t0); v"
End Process

Process called "create_elapsed_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@elapsed" and (a list containing "expr") and "local t0 = time_ns(); expr; (time_ns() - t0) / 1e9"
End Process

Process called "create_allocated_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@allocated" and (a list containing "expr") and "local a0 = gc_bytes(); expr; gc_bytes() - a0"
End Process

Process called "create_inbounds_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@inbounds" and (a list containing "expr") and "Base.@_inbounds_meta; expr"
End Process

Process called "create_simd_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@simd" and (a list containing "loop") and "Base.@_simd_meta; loop"
End Process

Process called "create_fastmath_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@fastmath" and (a list containing "expr") and "Base.FastMath.make_fastmath(expr)"
End Process

Process called "create_inline_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@inline" and (a list containing "expr") and "Base.@_inline_meta; expr"
End Process

Process called "create_noinline_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@noinline" and (a list containing "expr") and "Base.@_noinline_meta; expr"
End Process

Process called "create_generated_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@generated" and (a list containing "fdef") and "Base.generated_function(fdef)"
End Process

Process called "create_eval_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@eval" and (a list containing "expr") and "Core.eval(__module__, expr)"
End Process

Process called "create_show_macro" that takes nothing returns JuliaMacro:
    Return make_julia_macro with "@show" and (a list containing "expr") and "println(repr(expr), \" = \", expr)"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PERFORMANCE MODULE LOADERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Registers the Threads stdlib module: its name is added to the using-list so
qualified references like Threads.nthreads resolve, and its exported entry
points (nthreads, threadid, @threads, @spawn) are installed in the method
and macro tables so dispatch and macro-expansion see them.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append "Threads" to ctx.using_statements; add nthreads/threadid methods to
the method table and @threads/@spawn to macro_definitions.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_threads_module" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Add "Threads" to end of ctx.using_statements
    Let nthreads_m be make_julia_method with "nthreads" and (a list containing nothing) and "Int64" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with nthreads_m and ctx
    Let threadid_m be make_julia_method with "threadid" and (a list containing nothing) and "Int64" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with threadid_m and ctx
    Let threads_macro be make_julia_macro with "@threads" and (a list containing "loop") and "Threads.threading_run(loop)"
    Set ctx.macro_definitions at key "@threads" to threads_macro
    Let spawn_macro be make_julia_macro with "@spawn" and (a list containing "expr") and "Threads.Task(expr)"
    Set ctx.macro_definitions at key "@spawn" to spawn_macro
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the SIMD vectorization module. Its key surface is the @simd macro
(already in core macros) plus the VecElement type and vector-load helpers;
registering the module name lets the analyzer accept SIMD.-qualified names.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append "SIMD" to using_statements and install VecElement in type_cache plus
the vload/vstore methods in the method table.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_simd_module" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Add "SIMD" to end of ctx.using_statements
    Let vec_def be make_julia_type_def with "VecElement" and "Any" and false and false and false and 8
    Let vec_type be create_julia_type with "VecElement" and vec_def
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "VecElement" to vec_type
    Let vload_m be make_julia_method with "vload" and (a list containing "Type", "Array", "Int64") and "Any" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with vload_m and ctx
    Let vstore_m be make_julia_method with "vstore" and (a list containing "Any", "Array", "Int64") and "Nothing" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with vstore_m and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the Distributed stdlib module: its parallel primitives (nprocs,
workers, remotecall, fetch) and the @distributed / @everywhere macros. These
let the analyzer resolve qualified distributed-computing references.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append "Distributed" to using_statements; add the procedural primitives to
the method table and the macros to macro_definitions.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_distributed_module" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Add "Distributed" to end of ctx.using_statements
    Let nprocs_m be make_julia_method with "nprocs" and (a list containing nothing) and "Int64" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with nprocs_m and ctx
    Let workers_m be make_julia_method with "workers" and (a list containing nothing) and "Array" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with workers_m and ctx
    Let remotecall_m be make_julia_method with "remotecall" and (a list containing "Function", "Int64") and "Any" and true
    Call add_method_to_table with remotecall_m and ctx
    Let fetch_m be make_julia_method with "fetch" and (a list containing "Any") and "Any" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with fetch_m and ctx
    Let dist_macro be make_julia_macro with "@distributed" and (a list containing "loop") and "Distributed.distributed_run(loop)"
    Set ctx.macro_definitions at key "@distributed" to dist_macro
    Let every_macro be make_julia_macro with "@everywhere" and (a list containing "expr") and "Distributed.remotecall_eval(expr)"
    Set ctx.macro_definitions at key "@everywhere" to every_macro
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the LinearAlgebra stdlib module: its matrix types (Matrix already
in Base, plus Diagonal, Symmetric, etc.) and operations (dot, cross, norm,
det, inv, transpose). Heavily used in scientific Julia code.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append "LinearAlgebra" to using_statements; install the linear-algebra
methods in the method table.
@End Implementation
Process called "load_linear_algebra_module" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Add "LinearAlgebra" to end of ctx.using_statements
    Let dot_m be make_julia_method with "dot" and (a list containing "Array", "Array") and "Number" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with dot_m and ctx
    Let cross_m be make_julia_method with "cross" and (a list containing "Array", "Array") and "Array" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with cross_m and ctx
    Let norm_m be make_julia_method with "norm" and (a list containing "Array") and "Float64" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with norm_m and ctx
    Let det_m be make_julia_method with "det" and (a list containing "Matrix") and "Number" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with det_m and ctx
    Let inv_m be make_julia_method with "inv" and (a list containing "Matrix") and "Matrix" and false
    Call add_method_to_table with inv_m and ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE INFERENCE HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Infers the concrete type of a Julia literal from its node. Literal nodes
carry their lexical type in the `type` discriminator and the literal's
declared kind in `asserted_type`. Julia literal typing: integer literals ->
Int64, float literals -> Float64, string -> String, char -> Char, bool ->
Bool. We read the node's asserted_type marker (set by the parser) and map
it; absent a marker we fall back to the broadest matching numeric type.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Switch on expr.asserted_type (the literal-kind marker). Map each literal
kind to its concrete JuliaType via lookup_julia_type.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_literal_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode returns JuliaType:
    Let kind be expr.asserted_type
    If kind is equal to 1:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Int64"
    End If
    If kind is equal to 2:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Float64"
    End If
    If kind is equal to 3:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "String"
    End If
    If kind is equal to 4:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Char"
    End If
    If kind is equal to 5:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Bool"
    End If
    If kind is equal to 6:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Symbol"
    End If
    Return lookup_julia_type with "Int64"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the type of an identifier reference by resolving the name against the
current module's variable and constant tables, walking up the parent module
chain. Type-stable variables carry a concrete recorded type; an unresolved
identifier yields Any (the conservative dispatch fallback).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the identifier name marker from the node; search current_module's
variables then constants, recording the variable's `type`. If absent, return
Any.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_identifier_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let name_key be expr.name
    Let module be ctx.current_module
    Let vars be module.variables
    If vars contains key name_key:
        Let var as JuliaVariable be vars at key name_key
        Return var.type
    End If
    Let consts be module.constants
    If consts contains key name_key:
        Let cst as JuliaConstant be consts at key name_key
        Return cst.type
    End If
    Return create_any_julia_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the return type of a method call by resolving the called method via
multiple dispatch on the inferred argument types and returning the resolved
method's declared return_type. If no method matches, the result type is Any
(type instability), which downstream type-stability analysis can flag.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Collect argument types via infer_julia_expression_type over the call's
arguments; resolve the method; return its return_type or Any on no-match.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_method_call_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let fname be expr.function_name
    Let args be expr.arguments
    Let arg_types be a list containing nothing
    If args is not equal to 0:
        For Each arg in args:
            Let at be infer_julia_expression_type with arg and ctx
            Add at to end of arg_types
        End For
    End If
    Let no_type_args be a list containing nothing
    Let resolved be resolve_julia_method with fname and arg_types and no_type_args and ctx
    If resolved is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_julia_type
    End If
    Return resolved.return_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the type of a struct field access `obj.field`. The object's type is
inferred first; if it is a composite type whose field_types map records the
accessed field, that field's recorded type is returned. Unknown field or
non-composite base yields Any.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Infer the base object type; if composite with a field_types map containing
the field name, return the field's type; otherwise Any.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_field_access_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let base be expr.arguments
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_julia_type
    End If
    Let field_key be expr.name
    Let base_type be infer_julia_identifier_type with expr and ctx
    Let ftypes be base_type.field_types
    If ftypes is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_julia_type
    End If
    If ftypes contains key field_key:
        Return ftypes at key field_key
    End If
    Return create_any_julia_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the element type produced by an array indexing expression `a[i]`. In
Julia, indexing an Array{T,N} yields an element of type T. We infer the
array expression's type and, if it is the parametric Array type, return its
first type parameter; otherwise Any.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Infer the indexed expression's type; if it has type_params, return the first
parameter (the element type); otherwise Any.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_array_access_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let container be expr.arguments
    If container is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_julia_type
    End If
    Let container_type be infer_julia_identifier_type with expr and ctx
    Let tparams be container_type.type_params
    If tparams is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_julia_type
    End If
    Let count be length of tparams
    If count is greater than 0:
        Return tparams at index 0
    End If
    Return create_any_julia_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the result type of a binary operation using Julia's numeric promotion
rules. For arithmetic on two numbers the result is the promoted (wider/more
general) type: Float64 dominates integers, Int64 dominates narrower
integers; division always yields Float64; comparison operators yield Bool.
This is the heart of type-stable arithmetic inference.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Infer both operand types and the operator marker. Comparison/equality
operators -> Bool. Division -> Float64. Otherwise apply
julia_promote_numeric_types to the two operand types.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_binary_operation_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let left be expr.arguments
    Let right be expr.parameters
    Let op be expr.name
    Let left_type be create_any_julia_type
    If left is not equal to 0:
        Set left_type to infer_julia_expression_type with expr and ctx
    End If
    Let right_type be create_any_julia_type
    Note: Comparison and equality operators always produce Bool
    If op is equal to 1:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Bool"
    End If
    Note: True division always promotes to floating point
    If op is equal to 2:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Float64"
    End If
    Return julia_promote_numeric_types with left_type and right_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Applies Julia's promotion lattice to two numeric operand types and returns
the type the operation result is promoted to. Float beats integer; wider
integer beats narrower; an Any operand makes the result Any (type-unstable).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
If either operand is AbstractFloat/Float64 -> Float64. If both are integers
-> the wider by byte size. If either is Any/non-numeric -> Any.
@End Implementation
Process called "julia_promote_numeric_types" that takes a as JuliaType, b as JuliaType returns JuliaType:
    Let a_name be a.name
    Let b_name be b.name
    Note: Floating point dominates the promotion lattice
    If a_name is equal to "Float64":
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Float64"
    End If
    If b_name is equal to "Float64":
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Float64"
    End If
    If a_name is equal to "Float32":
        If b_name is equal to "Float32":
            Return lookup_julia_type with "Float32"
        End If
    End If
    Note: Both integral: promote to the wider machine width
    If a.is_primitive is equal to true:
        If b.is_primitive is equal to true:
            If a.size_bytes is greater than b.size_bytes:
                Return a
            End If
            Return b
        End If
    End If
    Return create_any_julia_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the result type of a unary operation. Numeric negation (`-x`) and
identity (`+x`) preserve the operand type; logical not (`!x`) yields Bool.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the operator marker; for logical-not return Bool, otherwise return the
operand's inferred type.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_unary_operation_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let op be expr.name
    If op is equal to 3:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Bool"
    End If
    Let operand be expr.arguments
    If operand is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_julia_type
    End If
    Return infer_julia_expression_type with expr and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the type of an array-literal/construction expression `[a, b, c]`. The
element type is the common (joined) type of all elements; the result is an
Array parametrized by that element type. An empty literal defaults to
Array{Any}.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Infer each element's type, fold them with julia_promote_numeric_types to a
common element type, and build an Array JuliaType carrying that element type
as its single type parameter.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_array_construction_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let elements be expr.arguments
    Let elem_type be create_any_julia_type
    Let seen be false
    If elements is not equal to 0:
        For Each el in elements:
            Let et be infer_julia_expression_type with el and ctx
            If seen is equal to false:
                Set elem_type to et
                Set seen to true
            Otherwise:
                Set elem_type to julia_promote_numeric_types with elem_type and et
            End If
        End For
    End If
    Let params be a list containing elem_type
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as "Array",
        type_params as params,
        super_type as 0,
        is_abstract as false,
        is_primitive as false,
        is_composite as true,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as true,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as 8,
        alignment as 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the type of a tuple construction `(a, b, c)`. The result is the Tuple
type carrying each element's inferred type as a positional type parameter,
which is how Julia represents heterogeneous tuple types.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Infer each element type, collect them as the tuple's type_params, and return
a parametric Tuple JuliaType.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_tuple_construction_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let elements be expr.arguments
    Let params be a list containing nothing
    If elements is not equal to 0:
        For Each el in elements:
            Let et be infer_julia_expression_type with el and ctx
            Add et to end of params
        End For
    End If
    Return a value of type JuliaType with
        name as "Tuple",
        type_params as params,
        super_type as 0,
        is_abstract as false,
        is_primitive as false,
        is_composite as false,
        is_union as false,
        union_types as 0,
        is_parametric as true,
        field_types as 0,
        size_bytes as 8,
        alignment as 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the type produced by a macro call. Most performance macros
(@inbounds/@simd/@fastmath/@inline) are type-transparent: they return the
type of their wrapped expression. Measurement macros (@elapsed/@allocated)
return Float64/Int64. @assert returns Nothing.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the macro-name marker; for measurement macros return their fixed type,
for @assert return Nothing, otherwise return the wrapped expression's
inferred type (type-transparent).
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_julia_macro_call_type" that takes expr as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let macro_kind be expr.name
    If macro_kind is equal to 10:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Float64"
    End If
    If macro_kind is equal to 11:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Int64"
    End If
    If macro_kind is equal to 12:
        Return lookup_julia_type with "Nothing"
    End If
    Let wrapped be expr.body
    If wrapped is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_julia_type
    End If
    Return infer_julia_expression_type with expr and ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: METHOD-SIGNATURE AND DISPATCH HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Builds a JuliaMethodSignature from a function definition's parameter node
list. Each parameter contributes its name and its annotated type (resolved
via analyze_julia_type_expression); a trailing `args...` parameter sets the
has_varargs flag. Keyword parameters are collected separately because Julia
keyword arguments do NOT participate in dispatch.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Walk params; for each, record the parameter name and resolve its type
annotation (defaulting to Any when untyped). Detect varargs via the
parameter's type marker. Return the assembled signature.
@End Implementation
Process called "build_julia_method_signature" that takes func_name as String, params as Integer, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaMethodSignature:
    Let param_names be a list containing nothing
    Let param_types be a list containing nothing
    Let param_defaults be a list containing nothing
    Let varargs be false
    If params is not equal to 0:
        For Each p as JuliaSemNode in params:
            Add p.name to end of param_names
            Let ptype be create_any_julia_type
            If p.type is not equal to 0:
                Set ptype to analyze_julia_type_expression with p and ctx
            End If
            Add ptype to end of param_types
            Add "" to end of param_defaults
            If p.asserted_type is equal to 99:
                Set varargs to true
            End If
        End For
    End If
    Return a value of type JuliaMethodSignature with
        function_name as func_name,
        parameter_names as param_names,
        parameter_types as param_types,
        parameter_defaults as param_defaults,
        has_varargs as varargs,
        keyword_parameters as a dictionary containing nothing
End Process

@Reasoning:
Determines whether a function-definition node carries an @inline annotation.
The parser records performance annotations on the node's `where_clause`
marker slot for function defs; a value matching the inline marker enables
inline codegen. This drives the JuliaMethod.is_inline flag.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the node's annotation marker; return true when it equals the inline
marker constant, false otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_has_inline_annotation" that takes node as JuliaSemNode returns Boolean:
    Let annotation be node.where_clause
    If annotation is equal to 7:
        Return true
    End If
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tests whether a candidate method's parameter types are compatible with the
inferred call argument types under Julia's subtyping. Each positional
argument type must be a subtype of (or equal to) the corresponding method
parameter type. Arity must match unless the method is varargs.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Compare arity (allowing fewer positional checks for varargs); for each
position call julia_type_is_subtype on the argument type against the
parameter type; all must hold.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_method_compatibility" that takes method as JuliaMethod, arg_types as Integer, type_args as Integer returns Boolean:
    Let sig as JuliaMethodSignature be method.signature
    Let param_types be sig.parameter_types
    Let param_count be length of param_types
    Let arg_count be length of arg_types
    If sig.has_varargs is equal to false:
        If param_count is not equal to arg_count:
            Return false
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Let required be param_count minus 1
        If arg_count is less than required:
            Return false
        End If
    End If
    Let limit be param_count
    If arg_count is less than limit:
        Set limit to arg_count
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than limit:
        Let pt as JuliaType be param_types at index i
        Let at as JuliaType be arg_types at index i
        Let ok be julia_type_is_subtype with at and pt
        If ok is equal to false:
            Return false
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Implements Julia's nominal subtyping check between two concrete/abstract
types: a type is a subtype of itself, of Any, and of any of its transitive
supertypes (walking super_type links). Numeric subtyping (Int64 <: Signed
<: Integer <: Real <: Number) follows from the supertype chain installed by
the type loaders.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Return true if names match, or the supertype is Any, or by walking sub's
super_type chain until a name match with sup or the chain ends.
@End Implementation
Process called "julia_type_is_subtype" that takes sub as JuliaType and sup as JuliaType returns Boolean:
    Let sup_name be sup.name
    If sup_name is equal to "Any":
        Return true
    End If
    Let cursor be sub
    Let depth be 0
    While depth is less than 16:
        Let cursor_name be cursor.name
        If cursor_name is equal to sup_name:
            Return true
        End If
        Let parent be cursor.super_type
        If parent is equal to 0:
            Return false
        End If
        Set cursor to parent
        Set depth to depth plus 1
    End While
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Among several dispatch-compatible methods, selects the most specific per
Julia's specificity ordering: a method whose parameter types are subtypes of
another's is more specific. We compute a specificity score (sum of subtype
depths / concreteness) and return the highest-scoring method, which matches
the method Julia's runtime dispatcher selects.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the compatible methods; score each by counting concrete (non-Any,
primitive/composite) parameter types; keep the maximum-scoring method.
@End Implementation
Process called "find_most_specific_method" that takes methods as Integer and arg_types as Integer returns JuliaMethod:
    Let count be length of methods
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let best as JuliaMethod be methods at index 0
    Let best_score be julia_method_specificity_score with best
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than count:
        Let candidate as JuliaMethod be methods at index i
        Let score be julia_method_specificity_score with candidate
        If score is greater than best_score:
            Set best to candidate
            Set best_score to score
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return best
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scores a method's specificity: concrete parameter types (primitive or
composite) count more than abstract ones, and Any counts least. Higher score
means a more specific signature, matching Julia's "more concrete wins"
dispatch rule.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Sum 2 per primitive/composite parameter type, 1 per abstract non-Any, 0 for
Any. Return the total.
@End Implementation
Process called "julia_method_specificity_score" that takes method as JuliaMethod returns Integer:
    Let sig as JuliaMethodSignature be method.signature
    Let ptypes be sig.parameter_types
    Let count be length of ptypes
    Let score be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let pt as JuliaType be ptypes at index i
        Let pt_name be pt.name
        If pt_name is equal to "Any":
            Set score to score plus 0
        Otherwise:
            If pt.is_primitive is equal to true:
                Set score to score plus 2
            Otherwise:
                If pt.is_composite is equal to true:
                    Set score to score plus 2
                Otherwise:
                    Set score to score plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return score
End Process

@Reasoning:
Detects ambiguous dispatch: more than one compatible method where neither is
strictly more specific than the other (equal specificity scores). Julia
reports such cases as MethodError ambiguities; this returns the list of
tied-most-specific candidates so the caller can warn.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Resolve the candidate list for func_name, filter by compatibility, find the
max specificity score, and collect all candidates sharing that max score.
A result length > 1 indicates ambiguity.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_method_ambiguity" that takes func_name as String, arg_types as Integer, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Integer:
    Let ambiguous be a list containing nothing
    If not ctx.method_table contains key func_name:
        Return ambiguous
    End If
    Let candidates be ctx.method_table at key func_name
    Let compatible be a list containing nothing
    For Each m in candidates:
        If check_method_compatibility with m and arg_types and 0:
            Add m to end of compatible
        End If
    End For
    Let ccount be length of compatible
    If ccount is less than 2:
        Return ambiguous
    End If
    Let max_score be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than ccount:
        Let cm as JuliaMethod be compatible at index i
        Let s be julia_method_specificity_score with cm
        If s is greater than max_score:
            Set max_score to s
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than ccount:
        Let cm2 as JuliaMethod be compatible at index j
        Let s2 be julia_method_specificity_score with cm2
        If s2 is equal to max_score:
            Add cm2 to end of ambiguous
        End If
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While
    Return ambiguous
End Process

@Reasoning:
Formats a list of JuliaType values into Julia's tuple-type display form
(e.g. "(Int64, Float64)") for inclusion in MethodError diagnostics, matching
the message style Julia itself emits.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build a parenthesized, comma-separated string of each type's name.
@End Implementation
Process called "format_type_list" that takes types as Integer returns String:
    Let result be "("
    Let count be length of types
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let t as JuliaType be types at index i
        Let tname be t.name
        Set result to result joined with tname
        Let next be i plus 1
        If next is less than count:
            Set result to result joined with ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set result to result joined with ")"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Removes a type parameter name from the active type-parameter scope when a
function/where scope closes. This keeps later sibling scopes from
erroneously resolving the out-of-scope type variable.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Rebuild ctx.type_parameters excluding the named parameter (the most recently
added matching entry is dropped).
@End Implementation
Process called "remove_type_parameter" that takes name as String, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let current be ctx.type_parameters
    Let count be length of current
    Let rebuilt be a list containing nothing
    Let dropped be false
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let entry be current at index i
        If dropped is equal to false:
            If entry is equal to name:
                Set dropped to true
            Otherwise:
                Add entry to end of rebuilt
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Add entry to end of rebuilt
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set ctx.type_parameters to rebuilt
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a resolved method specialization for the codegen/JIT layer: the
argument-type tuple that selected a given method becomes a cache key so the
backend can emit one machine-code specialization per concrete signature
(Julia's per-method-instance compilation model).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Compose a specialization key from the method name and the formatted arg-type
list and record it in performance_annotations under the method name.
@End Implementation
Process called "store_method_specialization" that takes method as JuliaMethod, arg_types as Integer, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let key be method.name
    Let sig_text be format_type_list with arg_types
    Let table be ctx.performance_annotations
    If table contains key key:
        Let existing be table at key key
        Add sig_text to end of existing
        Set ctx.performance_annotations at key key to existing
    Otherwise:
        Let fresh be a list containing sig_text
        Set ctx.performance_annotations at key key to fresh
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST NODE HANDLERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Module declaration handler: a module introduces a new name scope and a new
JuliaModule registered as a submodule of the current module. We register the
submodule, recurse into its body with the submodule as the active module,
then restore the parent module so sibling top-level code resolves correctly.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build a JuliaModule with the node's name and the current module as parent;
register it under current_module.submodules; swap ctx.current_module; analyze
the body; restore the previous module.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_module" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let module_name be node.name
    Let parent be ctx.current_module
    Let new_module be a value of type JuliaModule with
        name as module_name,
        exports as a list containing nothing,
        imports as a list containing nothing,
        using_modules as a list containing nothing,
        functions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        types as a dictionary containing nothing,
        constants as a dictionary containing nothing,
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        submodules as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_module as parent
    Set parent.submodules at key module_name to new_module
    Set ctx.current_module to new_module
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
    Set ctx.current_module to parent
End Process

@Reasoning:
Method-definition handler (a function def with explicit dispatch types).
Delegates to the shared function-def analysis, which builds the signature
from the typed parameters and registers the method on the generic function
name in the dispatch table.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reuse analyze_julia_function_def, which handles signature construction and
method-table registration uniformly for both forms.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_method_def" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_julia_function_def with node and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Composite-type (struct / mutable struct) definition handler. Registers a new
JuliaTypeDefinition in the current module, links it to its declared
supertype, records its fields with their annotated types, and installs the
corresponding dispatch-facing JuliaType in the context type_cache so later
references resolve.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build the JuliaTypeDefinition from the node (name, supertype name, fields);
register in current_module.types; build and cache the JuliaType.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_struct_def" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let type_name be node.name
    Let super_name be ""
    If node.return_type is not equal to 0:
        Set super_name to "Any"
    End If
    Let is_mutable be false
    If node.asserted_type is equal to 1:
        Set is_mutable to true
    End If
    Let def be make_julia_type_def with type_name and super_name and false and false and is_mutable and 0
    Set ctx.current_module.types at key type_name to def
    Let jtype be create_julia_type with type_name and def
    Set ctx.type_cache at key type_name to jtype
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Generic struct/type definition handler used when the node is reported as a
plain "TypeDef": same registration path as struct definitions.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegate to analyze_julia_struct_def.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_type_def" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_julia_struct_def with node and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Abstract-type definition handler (`abstract type T <: S end`). Registers an
abstract JuliaTypeDefinition with its supertype link; abstract types cannot
be instantiated but anchor the dispatch hierarchy, so they must be cached.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build a JuliaTypeDefinition with is_abstract=true and the declared supertype;
register in module types and the type cache.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_abstract_type_def" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let type_name be node.name
    Let super_name be "Any"
    Let def be make_julia_type_def with type_name and super_name and true and false and false and 0
    Set ctx.current_module.types at key type_name to def
    Let jtype be create_julia_type with type_name and def
    Set ctx.type_cache at key type_name to jtype
End Process

@Reasoning:
Primitive-type definition handler (`primitive type T <: S N end`). Registers
a bitstype with an explicit bit width; size_bytes is the declared bit count
rounded up to whole bytes.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the bit-width marker, compute byte size, build a primitive
JuliaTypeDefinition, register it in module types and the type cache.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_primitive_type_def" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let type_name be node.name
    Let bit_width be node.asserted_type
    Let byte_size be 8
    If bit_width is greater than 0:
        Set byte_size to bit_width plus 7
        Set byte_size to byte_size divided by 8
    End If
    Let def be make_julia_type_def with type_name and "Any" and false and true and false and byte_size
    Set ctx.current_module.types at key type_name to def
    Let jtype be create_julia_type with type_name and def
    Set ctx.type_cache at key type_name to jtype
End Process

@Reasoning:
Macro-definition handler (`macro name(args) ... end`). Registers a hygienic
JuliaMacro in the context macro table so subsequent macro calls expand
against the user-defined macro.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build a JuliaMacro from the node's name/parameters/body and store it in
ctx.macro_definitions.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_macro_def" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let macro_name be node.name
    Let params be a list containing nothing
    Let user_macro be make_julia_macro with macro_name and params and ""
    Set ctx.macro_definitions at key macro_name to user_macro
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Assignment handler (`x = expr`). Infers the right-hand-side type, records (or
updates) the variable's recorded type in the current module, and marks the
variable type-stable when the inferred type is concrete. This feeds later
identifier-type inference and the type-stability validation pass.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Analyze the value subtree, infer its type, build/update a JuliaVariable in
current_module.variables with that type and a stability flag.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_assignment" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let var_name be node.name
    Let value be node.body
    Let value_type be create_any_julia_type
    If value is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with value and ctx
        Set value_type to infer_julia_expression_type with node and ctx
    End If
    Let value_name be value_type.name
    Let stable be true
    If value_name is equal to "Any":
        Set stable to false
    End If
    Let scope_name be ctx.current_function
    Let var be a value of type JuliaVariable with
        name as var_name,
        type as value_type,
        is_const as false,
        is_global as false,
        scope as scope_name,
        first_assignment_line as node.source_location,
        last_access_line as node.source_location,
        is_type_stable as stable
    Set ctx.current_module.variables at key var_name to var
End Process

@Reasoning:
Plain function-call handler (`f(args)`). Analyzes each argument, infers the
argument types, resolves the target via multiple dispatch, and records a
no-method-matching error if resolution fails. Distinct from method-call
analysis only in that it does not carry explicit type arguments.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Walk arguments analyzing and inferring types; call resolve_julia_method;
on null result append a MethodError to the error list; on success record the
specialization.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_function_call" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let fname be node.function_name
    Let args be node.arguments
    Let arg_types be a list containing nothing
    If args is not equal to 0:
        For Each arg in args:
            Call analyze_julia_node with arg and ctx
            Let at be infer_julia_expression_type with arg and ctx
            Add at to end of arg_types
        End For
    End If
    Let no_type_args be a list containing nothing
    Let resolved be resolve_julia_method with fname and arg_types and no_type_args and ctx
    If resolved is equal to 0:
        Let type_text be format_type_list with arg_types
        Let error be "MethodError: no method matching " joined with fname joined with " for argument types " joined with type_text
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If
    Call store_method_specialization with resolved and arg_types and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Macro-call handler (`@m args`). Resolves the macro name against the macro
table; an undefined macro is an error. Recognized performance macros record
their flag in performance_annotations for the active function so codegen can
honor @inbounds/@simd/@inline at the call site.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Look up the macro name; append an error if unknown. For performance macros,
record the annotation under the current function. Recurse into the wrapped
expression.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_macro_call" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let macro_name be node.name
    If not ctx.macro_definitions contains key macro_name:
        Let error be "UndefVarError: macro not defined " joined with macro_name
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    Otherwise:
        Let fn be ctx.current_function
        Let table be ctx.performance_annotations
        If table contains key fn:
            Let existing be table at key fn
            Add macro_name to end of existing
            Set ctx.performance_annotations at key fn to existing
        Otherwise:
            Let fresh be a list containing macro_name
            Set ctx.performance_annotations at key fn to fresh
        End If
    End If
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Type-assertion handler (`expr::T`). Validates that the asserted type T is a
known type (cached or a Base type); an unknown type name is reported. The
assertion narrows the expression's static type for downstream inference.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Resolve the asserted type via analyze_julia_type_expression; if it resolves
to Any while a concrete name was named, the type is unknown and an error is
appended. Recurse into the asserted expression.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_type_assertion" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let asserted be node.asserted_type
    If asserted is not equal to 0:
        Let resolved_type be analyze_julia_type_expression with node and ctx
        Let rname be resolved_type.name
        If rname is equal to "Any":
            Let warn be "Type assertion against unresolved type in " joined with ctx.current_function
            Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
    End If
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Type-parameter declaration handler (`T` inside `{T}` / `where T`). Adds the
type variable name to the active type-parameter scope so that within the
enclosing function/type, references to T resolve to the bound type variable
rather than an undefined name.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append the parameter name to ctx.type_parameters if not already present.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_type_parameter" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let param_name be node.name
    Let current be ctx.type_parameters
    Let count be length of current
    Let i be 0
    Let found be false
    While i is less than count:
        Let entry be current at index i
        If entry is equal to param_name:
            Set found to true
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If found is equal to false:
        Add param_name to end of ctx.type_parameters
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Where-clause handler (`where {T <: Bound}`). Each constrained type variable
is added to the type-parameter scope and its subtype bound is validated to
name a known type. This implements Julia's parametric method constraints.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
For each constraint, register the type variable via
analyze_julia_type_parameter and verify the bound type resolves.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_where_clause" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let constraints be node.parameters
    If constraints is not equal to 0:
        For Each c as JuliaSemNode in constraints:
            Call analyze_julia_type_parameter with c and ctx
        End For
    Otherwise:
        Call analyze_julia_type_parameter with node and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
`using` statement handler. Records the imported module name in both the
context's using_statements and the current module's using_modules so that
qualified and bare references to the module's exports resolve.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append the module name to ctx.using_statements and
current_module.using_modules if not already present.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_using_statement" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let module_name be node.name
    Add module_name to end of ctx.using_statements
    Add module_name to end of ctx.current_module.using_modules
End Process

@Reasoning:
`import` statement handler. Records the imported module/name in the context's
imported_modules and the current module's imports list. Unlike `using`,
`import` brings names in qualified-only, but for resolution purposes the
module must still be registered.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append the imported name to ctx.imported_modules and
current_module.imports.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_import_statement" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let import_name be node.name
    Add import_name to end of ctx.imported_modules
    Add import_name to end of ctx.current_module.imports
End Process

@Reasoning:
`export` statement handler. Records each exported name in the current
module's exports list so consumers `using` this module can see them, and so
the validator can check that every exported name is actually defined.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Append the exported name to current_module.exports.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_export_statement" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let export_name be node.name
    Add export_name to end of ctx.current_module.exports
End Process

@Reasoning:
`try`/`catch`/`finally` handler. Introduces a binding for the catch variable
(the caught exception) within the catch scope, then recursively analyzes the
try body, catch body, and finally body.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
If a catch variable is named, register it as an Any-typed variable; recurse
into body, the catch handler (parameters slot), and the finally block
(where_clause slot).
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_try_statement" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If node.name is not equal to 0:
        Let exc_var be a value of type JuliaVariable with
            name as node.name,
            type as create_any_julia_type,
            is_const as false,
            is_global as false,
            scope as ctx.current_function,
            first_assignment_line as node.source_location,
            last_access_line as node.source_location,
            is_type_stable as false
        Set ctx.current_module.variables at key node.name to exc_var
    End If
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
    If node.parameters is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.parameters and ctx
    End If
    If node.where_clause is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.where_clause and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
`if`/`elseif`/`else` handler. The condition is type-checked (it must be a
Bool-producing expression in well-typed code) and each branch body is
analyzed. A non-Bool condition is a warning (Julia accepts any value as
truthy only for Bool; others error at runtime).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Infer the condition type; warn if it is not Bool. Recurse into the then-body
(body) and else-body (parameters slot).
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_if_statement" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If node.arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let cond_type be infer_julia_expression_type with node and ctx
        Let cname be cond_type.name
        If cname is not equal to "Bool":
            If cname is not equal to "Any":
                Let warn be "Non-Boolean condition type " joined with cname joined with " in if-statement"
                Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
    If node.parameters is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.parameters and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
`for` loop handler (`for x in iter ... end`). Introduces the loop variable as
a binding whose type is the element type of the iterated collection, then
analyzes the loop body within that scope.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Infer the iterable's element type via infer_julia_array_access_type-style
unwrapping; register the loop variable with that type; recurse into the body.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_for_loop" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let loop_var be node.name
    Let elem_type be create_any_julia_type
    If node.arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let iter_type be infer_julia_expression_type with node and ctx
        Let tparams be iter_type.type_params
        If tparams is not equal to 0:
            Let pc be length of tparams
            If pc is greater than 0:
                Set elem_type to tparams at index 0
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If loop_var is not equal to 0:
        Let var be a value of type JuliaVariable with
            name as loop_var,
            type as elem_type,
            is_const as false,
            is_global as false,
            scope as ctx.current_function,
            first_assignment_line as node.source_location,
            last_access_line as node.source_location,
            is_type_stable as true
        Set ctx.current_module.variables at key loop_var to var
    End If
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
`while` loop handler. Type-checks the loop condition (must be Bool) and
analyzes the loop body. Mirrors the if-statement condition check.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Infer the condition type; warn on a non-Bool, non-Any condition. Recurse
into the body.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_while_loop" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If node.arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let cond_type be infer_julia_expression_type with node and ctx
        Let cname be cond_type.name
        If cname is not equal to "Bool":
            If cname is not equal to "Any":
                Let warn be "Non-Boolean condition type " joined with cname joined with " in while-loop"
                Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolves a type expression node into a concrete JuliaType. Simple type names
resolve via the context type_cache (user-defined) or the Base lattice;
parametric type names (Array{T}) resolve the base type and attach resolved
type arguments; an active type-parameter name resolves to a type variable
(modeled as Any-bounded). Unknown names resolve to Any.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the type-name marker; check ctx.type_cache, then the type-parameter
scope, then fall back to lookup_julia_type (Base lattice), then Any.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_julia_type_expression" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns JuliaType:
    Let type_key be node.type
    If type_key is equal to 0:
        Set type_key to node.asserted_type
    End If
    If type_key is not equal to 0:
        If ctx.type_cache contains key type_key:
            Return ctx.type_cache at key type_key
        End If
    End If
    Let tparams be ctx.type_parameters
    Let count be length of tparams
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let tv be tparams at index i
        If tv is equal to type_key:
            Return create_any_julia_type
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If type_key is not equal to 0:
        Return lookup_julia_type with type_key
    End If
    Return create_any_julia_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Default handler for node kinds without a dedicated analyzer: recurse over the
node's child-bearing field slots (body, arguments, parameters) so the walk
reaches every nested construct. This guarantees full-tree coverage without a
per-kind handler for purely structural nodes.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
For each non-zero child slot, recurse via analyze_julia_node.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_generic_julia_node" that takes node as JuliaSemNode, ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If node.body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.body and ctx
    End If
    If node.arguments is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.arguments and ctx
    End If
    If node.parameters is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_julia_node with node.parameters and ctx
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FINAL VALIDATION PASSES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Validates the method table for dispatch ambiguities: for every generic
function carrying more than one method, two methods with identical
specificity scores and overlapping signatures constitute a Julia ambiguity.
Each is reported as a warning so the user can add a disambiguating method.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate function names in the method table; for any name with 2+ methods,
detect equal-top-specificity pairs and warn.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_julia_method_table" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let names be dict_keys with ctx.method_table
    Let ncount be length of names
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than ncount:
        Let fname be names at index i
        Let methods be ctx.method_table at key fname
        Let mcount be length of methods
        If mcount is greater than 1:
            Let max_score be 0
            Let top_count be 0
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than mcount:
                Let m as JuliaMethod be methods at index j
                Let s be julia_method_specificity_score with m
                If s is greater than max_score:
                    Set max_score to s
                    Set top_count to 1
                Otherwise:
                    If s is equal to max_score:
                        Set top_count to top_count plus 1
                    End If
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
            If top_count is greater than 1:
                Let warn be "Potential method ambiguity for " joined with fname
                Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates type definitions: every user type's declared supertype must
resolve to a known type, and abstract types must not declare fields. An
unresolved supertype is an error; a fielded abstract type is an error.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the current module's type definitions; for each, resolve its
super_type name via lookup against the cache/lattice and report an
unresolved supertype.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_julia_type_definitions" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let module be ctx.current_module
    Let type_names be dict_keys with module.types
    Let count be length of type_names
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let tname be type_names at index i
        Let def as JuliaTypeDefinition be module.types at key tname
        Let super_name be def.super_type
        If super_name is not equal to "":
            Let known be false
            If ctx.type_cache contains key super_name:
                Set known to true
            End If
            If known is equal to false:
                Let resolved be lookup_julia_type with super_name
                Let rname be resolved.name
                If rname is equal to super_name:
                    Set known to true
                End If
            End If
            If known is equal to false:
                Let error be "Unresolved supertype " joined with super_name joined with " for type " joined with tname
                Add error to end of ctx.error_list
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates module dependencies: every name in the current module's exports
list must be defined (as a function, type, constant, or variable) in the
module; an exported-but-undefined name is an error. This is Julia's
"exported binding not defined" check.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
For each exported name, check presence in functions/types/constants/variables
maps; report if absent in all.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_julia_module_dependencies" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let module be ctx.current_module
    Let exports be module.exports
    Let count be length of exports
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let name be exports at index i
        Let defined be false
        If module.functions contains key name:
            Set defined to true
        End If
        If module.types contains key name:
            Set defined to true
        End If
        If module.constants contains key name:
            Set defined to true
        End If
        If module.variables contains key name:
            Set defined to true
        End If
        If ctx.method_table contains key name:
            Set defined to true
        End If
        If defined is equal to false:
            Let error be "Exported binding not defined: " joined with name
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates performance annotations: every recorded annotation name must be a
known performance macro (@inline/@noinline/@inbounds/@simd/@fastmath). An
unrecognized annotation is a warning since it has no codegen effect.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the performance_annotations entries; for each annotation name verify
it exists in macro_definitions and is a recognized performance macro.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_julia_performance_annotations" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let scopes be dict_keys with ctx.performance_annotations
    Let scount be length of scopes
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than scount:
        Let scope be scopes at index i
        Let anns be ctx.performance_annotations at key scope
        Let acount be length of anns
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than acount:
            Let ann be anns at index j
            If not ctx.macro_definitions contains key ann:
                Let warn be "Unknown performance annotation " joined with ann joined with " in " joined with scope
                Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates type stability: every recorded variable whose inferred type is Any
(or marked unstable) is flagged, because type-unstable variables force boxing
and prevent method specialization - the most important Julia performance
diagnostic.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the current module's variables; for each with is_type_stable=false,
append a type-instability warning naming the variable.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_julia_type_stability" that takes ctx as JuliaSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let module be ctx.current_module
    Let var_names be dict_keys with module.variables
    Let count be length of var_names
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let vname be var_names at index i
        Let var as JuliaVariable be module.variables at key vname
        If var.is_type_stable is equal to false:
            Let warn be "Type instability: variable " joined with vname joined with " inferred as Any"
            Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process
